FastRecon â€“ Automated Attack Surface Mapping Tool

ğŸ“Œ Overview

FastRecon is a lightweight automation script designed to assist security practitioners, students, and defenders in performing initial reconnaissance and attack surface mapping for web-facing assets.

The tool chains together well-known open-source utilities to quickly identify:
-Exposed subdomains
-Live hosts
-Common web services and ports
-Potential web vulnerabilities (via template-based scanning)

FastRecon is intended strictly for authorized environments, such as:
-Personal labs
-Training platforms (e.g. TryHackMe, Hack The Box)
-Bug bounty programs
-Internal security assessments

ğŸ¯ Purpose & Use Case

During real-world assessments, reconnaissance often involves repetitive manual steps:
-Enumerating subdomains
-Checking which hosts are alive
-Identifying common web services
-Creating web targets for further testing

FastRecon automates this early recon phase, allowing analysts to:
-Save time
-Reduce human error
-Focus on analysis instead of setup

This tool does not perform exploitation â€” it only gathers and organizes publicly accessible information.

ğŸ§  How It Works

FastRecon follows a clear, staged workflow:

1ï¸âƒ£ Subdomain Enumeration

Uses assetfinder to discover subdomains related to the target domain

Results are deduplicated and stored for later stages

2ï¸âƒ£ Live Host Detection

Checks discovered subdomains for open HTTP (80) and HTTPS (443) ports

Filters out inactive or unreachable hosts

3ï¸âƒ£ Common Port Scanning

Scans a small, focused list of common web ports:

80, 443, 8080, 8000, 8443, 3000

Uses nmap with conservative timing to minimize noise

4ï¸âƒ£ Web Target Construction

Builds valid http:// and https:// URLs based on open ports

Produces a clean list of web targets for further inspection

5ï¸âƒ£ Visual Recon (Optional Context)

Uses gowitness to capture screenshots of discovered web services

Helps analysts quickly identify login panels, dashboards, or APIs

6ï¸âƒ£ Template-Based Vulnerability Scanning

Runs nuclei using community HTTP templates

Focuses only on:
-critical
-high
-medium severity findings

No intrusive or exploit-based templates are used

7ï¸âƒ£ Structured Reporting

Outputs both human-readable files and a JSON report

Makes results easy to parse, share, or integrate into other tools

